claims:
Claims 1. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics, the cartridge comprising: a cartridge housing defining a plurality of operational volumes, at least some of said plurality of operational volumes being mutually linearly aligned; and a fluid solution transporter operative to transfer fluid solutions from at least one of said plurality of operational volumes to at least another of said plurality of operational volumes, said fluid solution transporter including a linearly displaceable transport element operative to sequentially communicate with interiors of said at least some of said plurality of operational volumes. 2. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics, the cartridge comprising: a cartridge housing defining a plurality of operational volumes; and a fluid solution transporter operative to transfer fluid solutions from at least one of said plurality of operational volumes to at least another of said plurality of operational volumes, said cartridge housing defining at least one septum which sealingly mutually separates said plurality of operational volumes. 3. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 2 and wherein said at least one septum includes a pair of septum portions which lie in mutually angled planes. 4. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 2 or claim 3 and wherein said at least one septum is penetrable by displacement of said fluid solution transporter along a first axis and is penetrable by another displacement of another penetrating element along a second axis angled with respect to said first axis. 5. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics, the cartridge comprising: a cartridge housing defining a plurality of operational volumes; and 

 a fluid solution transporter operative to transfer fluid solutions from at least one of said plurality of operational volumes to at least another of said plurality of operational volumes, at least one of said plurality of operational volumes containing at least one magnet. 6. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 2 -5 and wherein said fluid solution transporter also comprises a linearly displaceable transport element operative to sequentially communicate with interiors of said at least some of said plurality of operational volumes. 7. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 1 or claim 6 and wherein said fluid solution transporter also comprises a piston assembly communicating with said linearly displaceable transport element. 8. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 7 and wherein said linearly displaceable transport element comprises a hollow needle. 9. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 7 or claim 8 and wherein said cartridge housing comprises first and second outer housing portions and a central portion and a septum portion, together defining at least some of said plurality of operational volumes. 10. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 9 and wherein said fluid solution transporter comprises a needle assembly which cooperates with said plurality of operational volumes. 11. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 10 and also comprising a sample insertion subassembly. 12. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 11 and also comprising a safety lock element removably mounted onto said cartridge housing. 13. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 12 and also comprising a flexible tube interconnecting said piston assembly with said linearly displaceable transport element. 14. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 13 and wherein said plurality of operational volumes include a multiplicity of operational volumes, at least some of which are configured to allow injection of fluid solutions thereinto. 15. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 14 and wherein most of said plurality of operational volumes each include a central slot through which said linearly displaceable transport element is adapted to extend. 16. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 15 and wherein most of said plurality of operational volumes are each sealed from each other by a septum which is sealingly penetratable by said linearly displaceable transport element, which is selectably positionable to selectably communicate with each of said most of said plurality of operational volumes. 17. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 16 and also comprising a microfluidic PCR array mounted within said cartridge housing. 18. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 17 and wherein at least one of said operational volumes defines an internal passageway to a port of said microfluidic PCR array. 19. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 18 and also comprising a sensor array mounted onto said cartridge housing. 20. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 19 and wherein at least one of said operational volumes defines an internal passageway to a port of said sensor array. 21. A cartridge for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of claims 7 - 20 and wherein said cartridge housing includes at least one waste conduit communicating with at least one operational volume operating as a waste collection volume. 22. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics, the method comprising: providing a cartridge having a plurality of operational volumes, at least some of said plurality of operational volumes being mutually linearly aligned; and transferring fluid solutions from at least one of said plurality of operational volumes to at least another of said plurality of operational volumes, said transferring fluid solutions including linearly displacing a transport element to sequentially communicate with interiors of said at least some of said plurality of operational volumes. 23. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 22 and wherein at least some of said plurality of operational volumes are mutually sealed by septa and said linearly displacing said transport element comprises penetrating said septa with said transport element. 24. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 22 or claim 23 and also comprising operating a piston assembly communicating with said transport element to transfer fluid solutions between ones of said plurality of operational volumes. 25. A method for use in in- vitro diagnostics according to claim 22 or claim 23 and also comprising transferring fluid solutions containing cellular material to a microfluidic PCR array mounted within said cartridge. 26. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 25 and also comprising transferring fluid solutions containing cellular material from said microfluidic PCR array to a sensor array associated with said cartridge. 27. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of the preceding claims 22 - 26 and also comprising injecting fluid solutions into some of said plurality of operational volumes prior to supplying cellular material thereto. 28. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to any of the preceding claims 22 - 24 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions comprises: locating a sample in a first operational volume together with a cell membrane breakdown material; locating an open end of a hollow needle in said first operational volume; drawing at least a portion of said sample and said cell membrane breakdown material into said hollow needle; and linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one second operational volume containing a cell lysis solution and magnetic beads. 29. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 28 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: repeatedly drawing said sample, and at least some of said cell membrane breakdown material, said cell lysis solution and said magnetic beads into said hollow needle and expelling said sample, and at least some of said cell membrane breakdown material, said cell lysis solution and said magnetic beads, from said hollow needle into said at least one second operational volume, thereby releasing nucleic acids from said sample and binding said nucleic acids to said magnetic beads. 30. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 29 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one third operational volume containing a wash buffer; drawing at least a portion of said wash buffer into said hollow needle into engagement with said magnetic beads together with said nucleic acids bound thereto; and repeatedly drawing said wash buffer and said magnetic beads, together with said nucleic acids bound thereto, into said hollow needle, thereby washing away cell debris and unbound nucleic acids from said magnetic beads. 31. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 30 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one fourth operational volume containing an elution buffer; drawing at least a portion of said elution buffer into said hollow needle into engagement with said magnetic beads, together with said nucleic acids bound thereto; and repeatedly drawing said elution buffer and said magnetic beads, together with said nucleic acids bound thereto, into said hollow needle, thereby disengaging said nucleic acids from said magnetic beads. 32. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 31 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one fifth operational volume containing at least one magnet; transferring said elution buffer and said magnetic beads, together with said nucleic acids disengaged therefrom, into said at least one fifth operational volume containing said at least one magnet, said at least one magnet attracting said magnetic beads; and 

 drawing said elution buffer, together with said nucleic acids, into said hollow needle. 33. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 32 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one sixth operational volume which communicates with a microfluidic PCR array; transferring said elution buffer and said nucleic acids into said microfluidic PCR array via said at least one sixth volume, said microfluidic PCR array generating amplified nucleic acids by amplifying said nucleic acids; and generating diluted nucleic acids by transferring said amplified nucleic acids from said PCR array to at least one seventh operational volume containing a dilution buffer. 34. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 33 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with said at least one seventh operational volume containing said diluted nucleic acids; and drawing said diluted nucleic acids into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with said at least one eighth operational volume which communicates with a sensor array; and transferring said diluted nucleic acids into operative engagement with said sensor array via said at least one eighth volume. 35. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 34 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one ninth operational volume which contains a discriminator reconstitution buffer; 

 drawing said discriminator reconstitution buffer into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one tenth operational volume which contains a discriminator; transferring said discriminator reconstitution buffer into said at least one tenth operational volume; repeatedly drawing said discriminator reconstitution buffer and said discriminator into said hollow needle and expelling said discriminator reconstitution buffer and said discriminator from said hollow needle into said at least one tenth operational volume, thereby generating a reconstituted discriminator; drawing said reconstituted discriminator into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one eleventh operational volume which communicates with said sensor array; and transferring said reconstituted discriminator into operative engagement with said sensor array via said at least one eleventh operational volume. 36. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 35 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one twelfth operational volume which contains a reporter reconstitution buffer; drawing said reporter reconstitution buffer into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one thirteenth operational volume which contains a reporter; transferring said reporter reconstitution buffer into said at least one thirteenth operational volume; repeatedly drawing said reporter reconstitution buffer and said reporter into said hollow needle and expelling said reporter reconstitution buffer and said reporter from said hollow needle into said at least one thirteenth operational volume, thereby generating a reconstituted reporter; 

 drawing said reconstituted reporter into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one fourteenth operational volume which communicates with said sensor array; and transferring said reconstituted reporter into operative engagement with said sensor array via said at least one fourteenth operational volume. 37. A method for use in in-vitro diagnostics according to claim 36 and wherein said transferring fluid solutions further comprises: linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one fifteenth operational volume which contains an array wash buffer; drawing said array wash buffer into said hollow needle; linearly displacing said open end of said hollow needle into communication with at least one sixteenth operational volume which communicates with said sensor array; and transferring said array wash buffer into operative engagement with said sensor array via said at least one sixteenth operational volume.
